Overview

Thus far in this module, we have explored and transformed data as well as created relatively simple plots using the tidyverse in R. But there is so much more that ggplot (and R) can do!

To help you in your projects, here are some other very useful tools for customizing plots from the tidyverse including

  • Faceting
  • Multi-panel figures

Setup

You should open your introR R project and continue working in your ggplot.R script. Remember to rerun the lines to load packages and now add the cowplot package.

Load packages
R v3.4 or newer

library(tidyverse)
library(cowplot)

R v3.3 or older

library(readr)
library(dplyr)
library(tidyr)
library(ggplot2)
library(cowplot)

And load and clean the raw data if you did not save your R project last time.

raw_dat <- read_csv("Saanich_Data.csv")
dat <- 
  raw_dat %>%
  select(Cruise, Date, Depth, Temperature,
         WS_O2, WS_NO3, WS_H2S) %>%
  filter(!is.na(WS_O2)) %>%
  rename(O2_uM=WS_O2, NO3_uM=WS_NO3, H2S_uM=WS_H2S) %>%
  mutate(Depth_m=Depth*1000)

Facetting

Rather than putting a lot of information into a single graphic, we can split the graphic into panels by certain features. This is called faceting.

Letâs return to this plot.

dat %>%
  select(Depth_m, O2_uM, NO3_uM, H2S_uM) %>% 
  gather(key="Chemical", value="Concentration", -Depth_m) %>% 
  
  ggplot(aes(x=Concentration, y=Depth_m, shape=Chemical, color=Chemical)) +
  geom_point() +
  scale_y_reverse(limits=c(200, 0))
## Warning: Removed 141 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

Many of our data points overlap so we may want to separate the geochemical variables into separate plots. Instead of independently creating 3 plots, we can instead add facet_wrap of the Chemical variable to the exact same code from above.

dat %>%
  select(Depth_m, O2_uM, NO3_uM, H2S_uM) %>% 
  gather(key="Chemical", value="Concentration", -Depth_m) %>% 
  
  ggplot(aes(x=Concentration, y=Depth_m, shape=Chemical, color=Chemical)) +
  geom_point() +
  scale_y_reverse(limits=c(200, 0)) +
  facet_wrap(~Chemical)
## Warning: Removed 141 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

Since the 3 variables are on somewhat different scales, we can also tell ggplot to scale the x-axes independently within each facet with the scales option.

dat %>%
  select(Depth_m, O2_uM, NO3_uM, H2S_uM) %>% 
  gather(key="Chemical", value="Concentration", -Depth_m) %>% 
  
  ggplot(aes(x=Concentration, y=Depth_m, shape=Chemical, color=Chemical)) +
  geom_point() +
  scale_y_reverse(limits=c(200, 0)) +
  facet_wrap(~Chemical, scales="free_x")
## Warning: Removed 141 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

You can also facet across multiple variables using facet_grid.

Themes

By default, ggplot uses a gray color scheme. However, there are a number of other themes that come with ggplot as well as many more in the additional package ggthemes. You can see many examples from ggplot or ggthemes.

Themes are simply added as another layer in ggplot.

dat %>%
  select(Depth_m, O2_uM, NO3_uM, H2S_uM) %>% 
  gather(key="Chemical", value="Concentration", -Depth_m) %>% 
  
  ggplot(aes(x=Concentration, y=Depth_m, shape=Chemical, color=Chemical)) +
  geom_point() +
  scale_y_reverse(limits=c(200, 0)) +
  facet_wrap(~Chemical, scales="free_x") +
  theme_bw()
## Warning: Removed 141 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

Or you can customize each aspect of your theme (either on its own or in addition to a premade theme) within theme. Here, we will only remove the color legend but you can explore many other options with ?theme.

dat %>%
  select(Depth_m, O2_uM, NO3_uM, H2S_uM) %>% 
  gather(key="Chemical", value="Concentration", -Depth_m) %>% 
  
  ggplot(aes(x=Concentration, y=Depth_m, shape=Chemical, color=Chemical)) +
  geom_point() +
  scale_y_reverse(limits=c(200, 0)) +
  facet_wrap(~Chemical, scales="free_x") +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(legend.position="none")
## Warning: Removed 141 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

Multiple panels

Faceting often gets you the multi-panel figure that you want. But sometimes you may want to combine multiple plot types, plots from different data sets, or perform some other sort of plotting that faceting does not support. Such plots can be achieved by a number of methods both inside and outside R. Here, we will show you one method using the cowplot package

First, we save the plots to be combined as R objects. Letâs use our last plot from above and clean up the labels a bit.

p1 <- dat %>%
  select(Depth_m, O2_uM, NO3_uM, H2S_uM) %>% 
  gather(key="Chemical", value="Concentration", -Depth_m) %>% 
  
  ggplot(aes(x=Concentration, y=Depth_m, shape=Chemical, color=Chemical)) +
  geom_point() +
  scale_y_reverse(limits=c(200, 0)) +
  facet_wrap(~Chemical, scales="free_x") +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(legend.position="none") +
  labs(y="Depth in m", x="Concentration in uM")

p1

As well as one showing the number of samples obtained at each depth.

p2 <- dat %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=Depth_m)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth=10) +
  scale_x_reverse(limits=c(200, 0)) +
  labs(x="", y="Total samples") +
  coord_flip() + # flip the x and y axes
  theme_bw() 

p2

We can then combine these plots with plot_grid. This function allows us to add panel labels, align the edges of plots, line up the axes, determine size (all shown below), and so much more!

p <- plot_grid(p1, p2, labels=c("A", "B"), align="h", axis="tb", rel_widths=c(3/4, 1/4))

p

Saving ggplots

Using ggsave you can save your ggplots to many different file types just by changing the extension in the file name.

Letâs save our ggplot to the projects folder as a pdf.

ggsave("saanich.pdf", p, width=10, height=6)

And sometimes after all this, itâs still not perfect. So, donât feel bad if you need to finalize plots for publication in another editor like Illustrator. Sometimes itâs a necessary evil.
